# 1️⃣ What is a Process?

A **Process** is a **program in execution**.

A program stored on disk is passive, but when it is loaded into memory and starts executing, it becomes a process.

### Process Components

* Program Code (Text Segment)
* Program Counter (PC)
* CPU Registers
* Stack (Function calls, local variables)
* Heap (Dynamic memory)
* Data Section (Global and static variables)

---

# 2️⃣ Process vs Program

| Program        | Process             |
| -------------- | ------------------- |
| Passive        | Active              |
| Stored on disk | Stored in memory    |
| Static         | Dynamic             |
| No execution   | Currently executing |

📌 **GATE Tip:** A single program can create multiple processes.

---

# 3️⃣ Process Control Block (PCB)

The **PCB** is a data structure maintained by the OS for every process.

It contains all the information needed to manage and resume a process.

### PCB Stores

* Process ID (PID)
* Process State
* Program Counter
* CPU Registers
* CPU Scheduling Information
* Memory Management Information
* Accounting Information
* I/O Status Information

📌 **Remember:** During a context switch, the CPU state is saved to the PCB.

---

# 4️⃣ Process States

### Five-State Model

```text
           New
            │
            ▼
         Ready
            │
      Scheduler
            ▼
         Running
        ↙      ↘
 Waiting      Ready
   │            ▲
   └────────────┘
            │
            ▼
        Terminated
```

### States

* **New:** Process is being created.
* **Ready:** Waiting for CPU.
* **Running:** Currently executing.
* **Waiting (Blocked):** Waiting for I/O or an event.
* **Terminated:** Finished execution.

---

# 5️⃣ State Transitions

* New → Ready: Process admitted.
* Ready → Running: CPU allocated.
* Running → Waiting: I/O request.
* Waiting → Ready: I/O completed.
* Running → Ready: Time slice expires (preemption).
* Running → Terminated: Process finishes.

---

# 6️⃣ Context Switching

A **Context Switch** occurs when the CPU switches from one process to another.

### Steps

1. Save current process state into its PCB.
2. Load the next process state from its PCB.
3. Resume execution of the new process.

📌 **Important:** Context switching is **overhead** because no useful user work is performed during the switch.

---

# 7️⃣ What is a Thread?

A **Thread** is the **smallest unit of CPU execution** within a process.

A process may have one or more threads.

Threads share:

* Code
* Data
* Heap
* Open files

Each thread has its own:

* Program Counter
* Registers
* Stack

---

# 8️⃣ Process vs Thread

| Process                      | Thread                       |
| ---------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Heavyweight                  | Lightweight                  |
| Separate address space       | Shared address space         |
| Communication is slower      | Communication is faster      |
| Higher creation cost         | Lower creation cost          |
| More context-switch overhead | Less context-switch overhead |

📌 **Frequently asked in GATE.**

---

# 9️⃣ Benefits of Multithreading

* Better CPU utilization.
* Faster execution.
* Resource sharing.
* Improved responsiveness.
* Lower overhead than processes.

---

# 🔟 Types of Threads

### User-Level Threads (ULT)

* Managed by user libraries.
* Fast to create.
* Kernel is unaware.

**Advantage:** Fast switching.

**Disadvantage:** A blocking system call can block all user threads in that process.

---

### Kernel-Level Threads (KLT)

* Managed by the operating system.
* Better concurrency.
* Higher management overhead.

---

# 1️⃣1️⃣ Multithreading Models

### Many-to-One

* Many user threads mapped to one kernel thread.
* Efficient but no true parallelism.

### One-to-One

* Each user thread maps to one kernel thread.
* Supports parallel execution.
* Higher overhead.

### Many-to-Many

* Many user threads mapped to many kernel threads.
* Balances concurrency and efficiency.

---

# 1️⃣2️⃣ Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

A **process is not the same as a program**.

---

### Trap 2

PCB stores the CPU context during context switching.

---

### Trap 3

Context switching **does not perform useful computation**; it is overhead.

---

### Trap 4

Threads share the **same address space**, but each has its **own stack**.

---

### Trap 5

A blocking system call in a Many-to-One model can block all user threads.

